snippet.textDisplay: @Doug DeMuro - Hey Doug, Just some input, on the 'Features' aspect of your DougScore profiling. I wish you would rate the features based on the decade the car was manufactured in (70s, 80, 90s, etc). It's just simply unfair to give a much older car a low score because it doesn't compete with something from 2018 or newer. I say this because some of these features these old cars had, despite it being outdated today, they were back in its time period the best you could get and considering that half the features of these new 2010s era cars have today did not even exist yet back in these past decades, it really doesn't give the older car (from the 90s decade in this case) a fair chance. Ever think about dividing up and reorganizing the DougScore to cater to decades instead of just comparing the oldest to the newest?

Good video a few additions for anyone that would like more information. . You could get a turbo on the Rolls Royce version. It was called a Flying Spur. Also in 1997-1999 the silver spur had a garrett turbo charger. True in 1990 you could not but a few years later you could



Also the low min oil discussion on the gauge is not for mineral oil as some comments say. It in fact does check the engine oil so you do not have to use the dip stick. The min oil line stands for minimum oil level which would give you the reading of minimum on the dipstick if you had low oil level.

snippet.textDisplay:
) Forbes magazine published an article titled, “China Killing Prisoners To Harvest Organs For Transplant: BMC Report Accuses China Of ‘Falsifying’ Data” by Zak Doffman, on November 16, 2019. The article states that China's claim of using a voluntary donation system for its billion-dollar organ transplant industry had been refuted by a report published in BMC Medical Ethics. Researchers found that the Chinese government falsified and manipulated official organ transplant datasets.

The article states, “In June, I reported on the China Tribunal in London, which found evidence of 'forced organ harvesting' from Chinese prisoners, including Falun Gong and Uighur Muslims. The Tribunal’s final judgment concluded that this 'forced organ harvesting has been committed for years...on a significant scale.' China has said that the practice has been outlawed, replaced with a system of voluntary donations. But a new report, published on November 14 in the BMC Medical Ethics journal, has refuted this, alleging that those claims of reform are being supported by the 'systematic falsification and manipulation of official organ transplant datasets in China.
